Overview

This document is meant to provide an overview of plotting in R using the {ggplot2} package. Theres definitely not enough room to cover everything, but hopefully its enough to get us started! In this walkthrough, well cover:

  • Plot Basics
  • Common Geoms
  • Faceting
  • Changing/Adding Labels
  • Changing Themes & Colors
knitr::opts_chunk$set(message = FALSE, warning = FALSE, fig.align = "center")

#loading useful packages
library(tidyverse)
library(palmerpenguins)

Plot Basics

This is way oversimplifying, but the three main things you need to consider when making a plot are the:

  1. data,
  2. aesthetics, and
  3. geoms.

The data is probably fairly self-explanatory. Its the data that youre planning to plot.

The aesthetics map variables in your data to visual characteristics of your graph. These include x and y positions (which are the ones youll use most often), but can also include things like color, fill, size, shape, and linetype (depending on what youre plotting/what type of plot youre producing).

The geoms are geometric objects, and they sort of combine the aesthetics and the data to produce something visual. Common geoms include lines, points, and columns/bars.

An example might help. Lets consider the following:

ggplot(data = penguins, aes(x = bill_length_mm, y = body_mass_g)) +
  geom_point()

Here were using the penguins data (from {palmerpenguins}), mapping the x position to the bill_length variable, mapping the y position to the body_mass variable, and telling ggplot to produce points (via geom_point()).

If we wanted, we could also color points by their species by specifying a color aesthetic:

ggplot(data = penguins, aes(x = bill_length_mm, y = body_mass_g, color = species)) +
  geom_point()

Note that this also gives us a legend on the side that tells us which species our colors correspond to.

Things to Notice

A few things you might notice in the above:

  • We used the + operator to combine our initial call to ggplot() with our call to geom_point(). This is how ggplot works, and it makes sense when you consider that ggplot actually layers things on top of one another. So what were actually doing in the above is creating a base graph where x position corresponds to the bill length variable, y position corresponds to the body mass variable, and color corresponds to the species variable. Were then layering points on top of this base graph.
  • geom_point() didnt actually take any arguments. This is because, by default, individual geoms inherit features defined in the initial call to ggplot(). If you ever want to override features, you can set inherit = FALSE within a geom. You can also define data and aesthetics within a given geom. For example, we could create the same plot as above with the following code:
ggplot() +
  geom_point(data = penguins, aes(x = bill_length_mm, y = body_mass_g, color = species))

Different Geoms

ggplot offers a ton of different geoms, and there are lots ggplot extensions that provide even more geoms. That said, there are a handful youll use most often. These include:

  • geom_point() for scatterplots,
  • geom_col() for barplots,
  • geom_line() for line graphs, and
  • geom_histogram() for histograms

Regardless of which geom you want to use, the basic use of ggplot is the same, although the way you think about the aesthetics will change.

Lets start with a histogram of body mass. This will automatically count penguins for you, so the only aesthetic we need to provide is the x variable:

ggplot(penguins) +
  geom_histogram(aes(x = body_mass_g))

Some other geoms might require you to summarize your data before plotting. For instance, geom_col() expects us to have one row per column. Lets imagine we want to plot the average mass by penguin species. Wed need to calculate the average first, then create our bar plot:

penguins %>%
  group_by(species) %>%
  summarize(avg_mass = mean(body_mass_g, na.rm = TRUE)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = species, y = avg_mass, fill = species)) + #note that 'fill' will fill our bars different colors
  geom_col()

Imagine we want to count the number of Gentoo penguins each year & create a line graph. Wed also need to do this counting beforehand:

penguins %>%
  filter(species == "Gentoo") %>%
  count(year) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = year, y = n)) + #note the default variable name when you count is 'n'
  geom_line()

Not the prettiest graph, but we can address that later.

Faceting

Faceting lets you create a bunch of stuck-together mini-plots within the same larger plot. This can be useful to separate different types of data, and is especially useful once we start to have a lot of variables we want to include in a single plot.

For example, lets revisit a previous plot:

ggplot(data = penguins, aes(x = bill_length_mm, y = body_mass_g, color = species)) +
  geom_point()

This includes all of our penguin species in the same plot. Another approach here might be to give each species its own facet. We can do this via facet_wrap() or facet_grid() (I tend to use wrap the vast majority of the time).

ggplot(data = penguins, aes(x = bill_length_mm, y = body_mass_g, color = species)) +
  geom_point() +
  facet_wrap(vars(species))

In this case, this doesnt really do much that our first plot didnt. However, what if we also wanted to look at penguins by species and by island. Faceting might allow us another way to convey this new variable:

ggplot(data = penguins, aes(x = bill_length_mm, y = body_mass_g, color = species)) +
  geom_point() +
  facet_wrap(vars(island))

This plot gives as a very different view of the data than our previous plot.

Changing & Adding Labels

One other common thing well want to do is add titles and change axis labels. By default, plots dont have titles and the axis (and color/fill) labels are whatever we pass into aes().

So consider the one of our earlier plots:

ggplot(data = penguins, aes(x = bill_length_mm, y = body_mass_g, color = species)) +
  geom_point()

We could improve this by adding a title and cleaning up the axis titles. We do this with labs() (short for labels).

ggplot(data = penguins, aes(x = bill_length_mm, y = body_mass_g, color = species)) +
  geom_point() +
  labs(
    title = "Penguin Plot!",
    subtitle = "A subtitle",
    x = "Bill Length (mm)",
    y = "Body Mass (g)"
  )

Changing the name of the legend is also doable, but requires a different function:

ggplot(data = penguins, aes(x = bill_length_mm, y = body_mass_g, color = species)) +
  geom_point() +
  labs(
    title = "Penguin Plot!",
    subtitle = "A subtitle",
    x = "Bill Length (mm)",
    y = "Body Mass (g)"
  ) +
  scale_color_discrete(
    name = "Penguin Species"
  )

We use scale_color_discrete() here (because we want to change options of our color scale, and it is discrete (i.e.categorical) rather than continuous). Then we change the name of this scale.

Changing Themes and Using Custom Colors

One other thing we can do to alter the appearance of our plots is to use a theme. There are some pre-built themes in ggplot as well as themes other people have made (you can check out the {ggthemes} package for lots of pre-built themes).

My favorite built-in theme is theme_minimal(). You can apply this theme via:

ggplot(data = penguins, aes(x = bill_length_mm, y = body_mass_g, color = species)) +
  geom_point() +
  labs(
    title = "Penguin Plot!",
    subtitle = "A subtitle",
    x = "Bill Length (mm)",
    y = "Body Mass (g)"
  ) +
  scale_color_discrete(
    name = "Penguin Species"
  ) +
  theme_minimal()

I have my own theme (theme_ee()) that I built thats part of my personal miscellaneous package. This is the one I use in most of my work:

#remotes::install_github(ekholme/eemisc) to install my personal package
library(eemisc)

ggplot(data = penguins, aes(x = bill_length_mm, y = body_mass_g, color = species)) +
  geom_point() +
  labs(
    title = "Penguin Plot!",
    subtitle = "A subtitle",
    x = "Bill Length (mm)",
    y = "Body Mass (g)"
  ) +
  scale_color_discrete(
    name = "Penguin Species"
  ) +
  theme_ee()

Another thing you might want to do is change the colors youre using. ggplot has some built in options, and there are tons of extension libraries offering color palettes (just google ggplot color palettes). For instance, lets use the new {tayloRswift} package, that has T-Swift-inspired colors:

#install.packages("tayloRswift") if you don't have it installed already
library(tayloRswift)

ggplot(data = penguins, aes(x = bill_length_mm, y = body_mass_g, color = species)) +
  geom_point() +
  labs(
    title = "Penguin Plot!",
    subtitle = "A subtitle",
    x = "Bill Length (mm)",
    y = "Body Mass (g)"
  ) +
  scale_color_taylor(palette = "taylor1989") +
  theme_ee()

You can see the packages GitHub repo for more info on the palettes available.

Another way to change colors is to just tell the plot the exact color you want. This is most useful when youre not using color to indicate (for example) a penguin species, but you just dont want your points to be black. We do this by passing the color argument to geom_point() (or any other geom) outside of the aes() call:

ggplot(data = penguins, aes(x = bill_length_mm, y = body_mass_g)) +
  geom_point(color = "red") +
  labs(
    title = "Penguin Plot!",
    subtitle = "A subtitle",
    x = "Bill Length (mm)",
    y = "Body Mass (g)"
  ) +
  theme_ee()

Closing Thoughts

{ggplot2} is very customizable, and this only scratches the surface of what you can do. That said, I think this provides a strong intro into ggplot, and it covers the foundations that will help you make clean plots to include in reports and whatnot.
